                  <persName id="t18310908-286-person2075">
                  ROBERT 
                  LANDER
               <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2075" type="surname" value="LANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2075" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2075" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-man. On the 27th of August, about half-past twelve o'clock at night, I was in Kingsland-road, and saw the prisoner standing by the gates of the parish stone-yard, in <placeName id="t18310908-286-crimeloc1469">Fleming-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-286-crimeloc1469" type="placeName" value="Fleming-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-286-crimeloc1469" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-286-off1466 t18310908-286-crimeloc1469"></join> - he turned round, and went towards the wall next the gates, where two shovels were handed over the wall to him - he went about forty yards with them under his arm; I stopped him; he said he had picked them up by the side of the gate, and would take them back.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-286-person2076">
                  JOHN 
                  WHITTY
               <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2076" type="surname" value="WHITTY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2076" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-286-person2076" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I hold a situation under the trustees of the poor. These shovels are their property; I left them locked up in the yard on the Saturday night.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had occasion to stop for a moment, and on turning my head I saw the shovels lay there; I carried them about forty yards, and then thought I would have no more to do with them - as I turned back, the Police-man came up.</p>
